JOHANNESBURG - Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula is cracking the whip on cable theft suspects. The minister visited an illegal cable theft melting factory in Ratanda, south of Heidelberg. READ: Our trains are not safe: Mbalula He accompanied officials on a tour of the facility where Prasa cables worth R2.6-million were recovered. The minister said a network of thieves process and transport the melted cables to Mozambique and to countries in Asia. Mbalula said, "this is a broken organisation -- it is a broken organisation which we are fixing," The minister stated security guards employed by Prasa were able to find the culprits which he said were usually outside contractors. Mbalula said culprits who have been found participating in copper theft should be charged with economic sabotage.